"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Kings chapters 12–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-12-14.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1kings.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1kings.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/1kings.json (prior chapters for continuity)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch12: Shechem assembly as tribal covenant-renewal site; Jeroboam's calves as political
  religion, not simple paganism — they invoke Exod 32 imagery deliberately
- Ch13: The old prophet episode illustrates the danger of secondary revelation
  overriding an explicit divine command; lion/donkey scene signals divine validation
  of the original command even in judgment
- Ch14: Shishak's invasion in year 5 of Rehoboam is confirmed by Egyptian
  archaeological evidence (Shishak relief at Karnak); qedeshim debated as
  male cult prostitutes or sacred functionaries
- Tirzah as northern capital after Shechem; masseboth and Asherah poles
  as Canaanite cultic objects absorbed into Israelite syncretism
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS1 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Rehoboam travels to Shechem for his coronation rather than Jerusalem. Shechem was the ancient site of tribal covenant-making — Jacob bought land there (Gen 33:19), Joshua assembled all Israel there for covenant renewal (Josh 24), and it was the first city Abram entered in Canaan (Gen 12:6). Its selection signals that the northern tribes demand a formal suzerain-vassal covenant ratification before granting loyalty, not mere dynastic succession.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jeroboam had fled to Egypt under Solomon (11:40) and remains there until news of Solomon's death reaches him. Egypt served as a standard refuge for political opponents of the Jerusalem court — the same pattern seen with Hadad the Edomite (11:17&ndash;19). His presence in Egypt at this moment sets up the tribal assembly's ability to summon him as their alternative.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The assembly sends for Jeroboam — a deliberate act of political theater. Bringing him from Egypt signals to Rehoboam that they have an alternative king ready. The assembly speaks collectively (<em>qāhal</em>), the covenantal assembly of all Israel, not merely a mob. This is formal treaty-negotiation language.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The petition uses suzerain-vassal treaty language: &ldquo;your father made our burden heavy&rdquo; — the corvée (<em>mas</em>) imposed by Solomon for his building projects (5:13&ndash;18) and the tribute demands on the twelve administrative districts (4:7&ndash;19). The northern tribes are invoking their covenant right to petition the king. The promise is conditional: &ldquo;we will serve you&rdquo; — the same verb used in covenant-loyalty contexts.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Rehoboam's three-day deliberation period follows standard ancient Near Eastern treaty protocol — a period for counsel and formal response. Three days appears throughout the OT as the customary interval for a significant decision or journey (cf. Gen 22:4; Josh 1:11). The adjournment is not weakness; it is the proper form.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The elders who &ldquo;stood before&rdquo; (<em>ʿāmᵉdû lipnê</em>) Solomon were the senior court officials of the Solomonic administration — men with decades of experience in the management of the empire and its tribute structure. In ancient Near Eastern wisdom tradition, elders embodied accumulated <em>ḥokmāh</em> (wisdom), and consulting them was the expected behavior of a good king (cf. Prov 11:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The elders' advice inverts the normal patron-client dynamic: the king should become <em>ʿeḇed</em> (servant) to the people. This language echoes the ideal of the servant-king — a concept known from Mesopotamian royal ideology where the king serves the gods by serving the people's welfare. Their counsel is fundamentally about covenant: a king who lightens burdens secures loyalty; a king who increases them risks revolt.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Rehoboam &ldquo;rejected&rdquo; (<em>ʿāzaḇ</em>) the elders' counsel — the same verb used for abandoning YHWH (1 Kgs 11:33). The young men he consults instead are his age-cohort (<em>yaldîm</em>, lit. &ldquo;boys&rdquo; or &ldquo;young men&rdquo;) who grew up with him in the court — likely sons of Solomonic officials, raised in an atmosphere of imperial luxury without exposure to the administrative realities that shaped the elders' judgment.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The question Rehoboam poses to the young men is identical to the one posed to the elders — which sets up the narrative contrast. The people's request to &ldquo;lighten the yoke&rdquo; (<em>qal meʿal ha-ʿōl</em>) uses the language of corvée and tribute that the Exodus narrative uses for Egyptian slavery (Exod 1:11&ndash;14; 2:11). The northern tribes are implicitly comparing Solomonic labor demands to Egyptian bondage.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;My little finger is thicker than my father's loins&rdquo; — a boastful comparison using sexually charged idiom. The young men advise Rehoboam to assert dominance through exaggeration. In honor-shame culture, such a declaration is a public claim of superior power and willingness to use it. It would have been heard as a direct insult to the petitioners' dignity and a rejection of the covenant form they sought.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Scorpions (<em>ʿaqrabbîm</em>) here refers not to the animal but to a type of whip with multiple pointed ends or barbed lashes — attested in Roman-era sources as <em>scorpio</em>. The escalation from &ldquo;whips&rdquo; to &ldquo;scorpions&rdquo; mirrors the kind of rhetorical boast known from ancient Near Eastern royal inscriptions, where kings claim to surpass their predecessors in power and severity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The assembly returns on the third day as Rehoboam specified. The narrative slows to mark the gravity of the moment: this assembly represents the entire northern tribal confederacy acting within its covenantal rights to seek treaty modification. Their orderly return shows this is not mob action but formal political procedure.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The narrator signals divine evaluation: Rehoboam &ldquo;answered the people harshly&rdquo; (<em>qāšāh</em>). The same root describes the hard (<em>qāšāh</em>) labor of Egyptian slavery in Exod 1:14. The echo is intentional — Rehoboam is cast in the role of Pharaoh, hardening his heart against the people's legitimate appeal.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Rehoboam implements the young men's advice word for word — establishing that his response was the result of a deliberate policy choice, not mere anger. The narrator will immediately explain the theological dimension in v15, but the human dimension is clear: a new king, insecure in his position, defaulted to the most aggressive posture available to him.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;This turn of events was from the LORD&rdquo; (<em>sᵉḇîḇâ hāyᵉtāh mēʾēt YHWH</em>) — the narrator interposes a theological explanation. The word &ldquo;from&rdquo; here does not eliminate human responsibility but frames Rehoboam's foolishness within YHWH's larger purpose. The reference is to 11:29&ndash;39, where Ahijah the prophet tore Jeroboam's cloak and promised him ten tribes because of Solomon's idolatry.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;What share do we have in David?&rdquo; (<em>mah-lānû ḥēleq bᵉḏāwid</em>) quotes the exact war cry used by Sheba son of Bichri in his revolt against David after Absalom's rebellion (2 Sam 20:1). The northern tribes are invoking a pre-existing separatist formula, signaling that the fault lines in the Davidic state run deep — this is not a new grievance but the resurfacing of an old one.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Rehoboam retains authority over &ldquo;the Israelites who were settled in the towns of Judah&rdquo; — a formulation that acknowledges the tribal complexity of the south: Judah, Benjamin, and scattered individuals from other tribes who had settled in Judahite towns. The Shechem coronation attempt has failed for the north but established Rehoboam as king in the south.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Adoram (or Adoniram, cf. 4:6; 5:14) had administered the forced labor (<em>mas</em>) under both David and Solomon — a career spanning decades. His stoning represents the northern tribes' visceral rejection of the corvée system. Public stoning was the community's ultimate judgment, typically reserved for capital crimes; applying it to the labor commissioner signals that the northerners regard the corvée itself as a capital offense against their covenant rights.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;To this day&rdquo; (<em>ʿad hayyôm hazzeh</em>) is a narrator's aside anchoring the story in the present of its first audience — likely written during the divided monarchy or early exile. The phrase acknowledges that the schism is a standing historical fact, not merely a past episode. The word &ldquo;rebellion&rdquo; (<em>pāšaʿ</em>) is the technical term for covenant breach.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The northern assembly formally installs Jeroboam as king. The tribe of Judah alone follows the house of David — Benjamin is absorbed into Judah's orbit but the text here focuses on Judah as the loyal remnant. Jeroboam's kingship is framed as emerging from the assembly's collective will, a contrast with the Davidic dynastic principle.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Rehoboam musters 180,000 warriors from Judah and Benjamin — a formidable military force. The narrative creates tension: will there be civil war? Benjamin's alignment with Judah here is significant — as the tribe of Jerusalem's northern border, Benjamin had strategic reasons to align with the Davidic throne. The description of the muster (&ldquo;chosen warriors to fight against the house of Israel&rdquo;) shows Rehoboam's intent to reconquer the north by force.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Shemaiah is titled &ldquo;man of God&rdquo; (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the standard designation for a prophet acting with divine authority (cf. Moses in Deut 33:1; the unnamed prophet of ch13). The word of God interrupts the military mobilization at precisely the moment of maximum tension.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The oracle addresses Rehoboam, all Judah, Benjamin, and &ldquo;the rest of the people&rdquo; — the full political entity of the southern kingdom in its broadest definition. YHWH's word is addressed to the king and the entire body politic simultaneously, which is characteristic of prophetic oracles that function as public proclamations rather than private counsel.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;This thing is from me&rdquo; (<em>mēʾittî hāyāh haddāḇār hazzeh</em>) — YHWH explicitly claims the schism as his own act. The prohibition against fighting &ldquo;your Israelite brothers&rdquo; (<em>ʾăḥêḵem bᵉnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) is significant: even in division, the northerners remain the kinsmen of the south. Shemaiah's word is obeyed — the army disperses. This stands as a counterexample to Rehoboam's earlier rejection of wise counsel.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Jeroboam fortifies Shechem in the Ephraimite hill country as his first capital — returning to the ancient tribal assembly site. Penuel, east of the Jordan near the Jabbok ford (cf. Gen 32:30&ndash;31), secures the Transjordanian flank against Aramaean pressure. Both sites are strategically chosen to defend the northern kingdom's heartland against external threats.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Jeroboam's internal monologue is unusual in biblical narrative — the narrator allows access to royal deliberation. The fear that &ldquo;the kingdom could easily revert to the house of David&rdquo; is politically astute: so long as the Jerusalem temple remained the only legitimate worship center, northern pilgrims would maintain emotional and religious ties to the south, creating a persistent centripetal pull.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The religious-political calculation is explicit: pilgrimage to Jerusalem means contact with Rehoboam's court, worship at the Solomonic temple, and the risk of reconsolidation around Davidic legitimacy. Jeroboam's concern is not theological but political — he correctly perceives that the Jerusalem cult is a mechanism of political integration that works against his dynasty.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The two golden calves at Bethel and Dan echo Aaron's golden calf at Sinai (Exod 32:4, 8), where the same formula appears: &ldquo;These are your gods, O Israel, who brought you up out of Egypt.&rdquo; Whether Jeroboam intends a direct allusion or reproduces an ancient Canaanite-Israelite iconographic tradition (YHWH depicted as enthroned on a bull), the narrator casts it through the Exodus lens as repetition of the primal apostasy. The calves likely functioned as thrones or pedestals for the invisible YHWH — similar to the cherubim in Jerusalem — but the iconography was irremediably compromised by the Sinai precedent.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Bethel, on the southern border of Ephraim, was already an ancient Israelite sanctuary — Jacob had his dream there (Gen 28:10&ndash;22) and named it &ldquo;house of God.&rdquo; Dan was the northernmost city, controlling the headwaters of the Jordan. Placing shrines at the geographic extremities (south and north) creates a territorial claim to the entire northern kingdom and provides accessible pilgrimage sites without the journey to Jerusalem.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;This became a sinful thing&rdquo; (<em>wayᵉhî hadd̠āḇār hazzeh lᵉḥaṭṭāʾt</em>) — the narrator's theological verdict. The phrase recurs in 13:34 regarding the house of Jeroboam and becomes the formulaic refrain for evaluating northern kings throughout Kings: they &ldquo;walked in the way of Jeroboam the son of Nebat, who caused Israel to sin.&rdquo; The people going to Dan to worship marks the success of Jeroboam's policy but the depth of the theological problem.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jeroboam builds <em>bêt bāmôt</em> (house/shrine of high places) and appoints priests from &ldquo;all sorts of people&rdquo; (<em>miqqᵉṣôt hāʿām</em>, lit. &ldquo;from the ends of the people&rdquo;) — those who were not of Levitical lineage. Israelite priestly law (Num 3:10; 18:7) reserved the altar for Levites/Aaronides; appointment of non-Levitical priests was a fundamental disruption of the cultic order and a second major apostasy alongside the calf-images.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jeroboam institutes a festival on the fifteenth day of the eighth month — deliberately one month later than the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkoth) in the seventh month (Lev 23:34). The parallel with Jerusalem's festival (&ldquo;similar to the festival in Judah&rdquo;) shows that Jeroboam is creating an alternative cultic calendar, not abolishing worship but redirecting it. Agricultural festivals were tied to harvest cycles; an eighth-month festival would correspond to a later northern harvest season, providing a plausible rationale to the people.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Jeroboam himself officiates at Bethel — going up to the altar he built, burning incense, and instituting the eighth-month festival &ldquo;which he had devised on his own&rdquo; (<em>bāḏāh millibô</em>, lit. &ldquo;invented from his heart&rdquo;). This phrase is the narrator's strongest condemnation: the festival calendar has no divine mandate but is a human invention. For a king to officiate at the altar is a usurpation of the priestly role — a pattern that will recur in the narrative of Uzziah's presumption (2 Chr 26:16&ndash;21).</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The &ldquo;man of God&rdquo; (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) who arrives from Judah is unnamed throughout the chapter — a deliberate literary choice that makes him a representative of prophetic authority rather than an individual. He arrives while Jeroboam is standing at the altar burning incense — the act just described in 12:33. The timing of his arrival at the very moment of Jeroboam's cultic presumption signals divine responsiveness.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The oracle names Josiah three centuries before his birth (2 Kgs 23:15&ndash;16 fulfills this). Such predictive naming is rare in the Hebrew prophetic tradition and would have been read as confirmation of the word's divine origin. The specific act predicted — burning human bones on the Bethel altar — reflects the practice of defiling sacred sites by scattering human remains on them, thus making them permanently impure (cf. Num 19:16).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A &ldquo;sign&rdquo; (<em>môpēt</em>) is given the same day — an immediate miraculous confirmation of the prophetic word. The split altar and spilled ashes are not merely destructive; they render the altar ritually impure and thus unusable. The sign functions as a preview of the eschatological judgment announced in v2.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jeroboam stretches out his hand and commands arrest — but the hand withers (<em>tîḇaš</em>). The image of the king's commanding hand rendered impotent at the moment of attempted violence against a prophet echoes the Exodus narrative where Pharaoh's power proves futile against YHWH's messenger. The withering is both a judgment and a demonstration: YHWH's authority over the king's physical body.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The altar splits and the ash falls — exactly as the man of God prophesied in v3. The fulfillment of the sign is instantaneous, validating the prophetic word before any action is taken against it. In ancient Near Eastern contexts, such signs were understood as divine authentication: the god who controls nature confirms his spokesman.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jeroboam's request — &ldquo;entreat the favor of the LORD your God&rdquo; (<em>ḥal-nāʾ et-pᵉnê YHWH ʾĕlōheḵā</em>) — is notable for the possessive: he says &ldquo;your God,&rdquo; not &ldquo;my God&rdquo; or even &ldquo;our God.&rdquo; This reveals that Jeroboam does not regard YHWH as his deity in any personal sense — he is requesting access to a power he acknowledges but does not worship. The restoration of the hand follows prayer, not repentance.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The king's hospitality offer — &ldquo;come home with me and refresh yourself (<em>sāʿad</em>) and I will give you a gift&rdquo; — uses the patron-client language of ancient Near Eastern court culture. Acceptance of royal hospitality created a reciprocal obligation and would have placed the man of God within Jeroboam's household network, effectively co-opting his independence. The gift (<em>maśśāʾ</em>) would have been substantial enough to create ongoing dependency.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The refusal is absolute even under hypothetically maximal conditions — &ldquo;even if you gave me half your palace.&rdquo; The man of God's independence from royal patronage is constitutive of his prophetic authority. A prophet who accepts royal hospitality becomes a court prophet; one who refuses remains free to speak inconvenient truth. The refusal pattern here will be tragically reversed in v19.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The divine command given before the mission was specific and threefold: no eating, no drinking, no returning by the same road. The prohibition against eating in Bethel has the character of herem-like ritual separation — the man of God is to pass through as an alien witness, not integrate into the community he judges. The different-route requirement may serve to prevent the Bethelites from intercepting him on the way back.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The man of God takes a different road and does not return through Bethel — initial obedience is complete. The narrative sets up a crucial detail: he is on the road, exposed, when the old prophet will find him. His compliance with the divine command is noted before the test arrives.</p>",
    "11": "<p>An old prophet (<em>nāḇîʾ</em> — standard term) lives in Bethel. His sons witness the events of the day and report them to him. The old prophet is not presented as false or evil at this point — but as a resident prophet of Bethel, he is institutionally embedded in the cultic system that Jeroboam has established. His role in what follows is theologically complex: he acts deceptively but his subsequent mourning (v30) and instructions (v31&ndash;32) show he understood the prophetic authority of the man of God.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The father asks which road the man of God traveled — a detail of geographic precision. The sons show him the route taken by the man of God from Judah. The old prophet's pursuit is motivated by something the text does not fully explain — perhaps curiosity, perhaps a desire for prophetic fellowship, perhaps something more sinister. The narrative leaves his initial motivation ambiguous.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The command to saddle the donkey and the immediate compliance of the sons establish the old prophet as a man of authority in his household. Donkeys were the standard transport for non-military travel in the ancient Near East; their use signals a deliberate pursuit rather than chance encounter.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The man of God is found sitting under an oak tree (<em>ʾēlāh</em>) — a resting tree on the road. The image of the prophet resting under a tree while on a divine mission will recur with Elijah under the broom tree (1 Kgs 19:4&ndash;5). The question &ldquo;Are you the man of God who came from Judah?&rdquo; establishes identity and confirms the old prophet knows who he is pursuing.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The old prophet repeats the king's invitation of v7 almost verbatim: &ldquo;Come home with me and eat bread.&rdquo; The parallel invitation from two different sources — first a king, then a fellow prophet — creates escalating pressure. Hospitality refusal was socially costly in honor-shame culture; refusing a king could be defended as prophetic independence, but refusing a fellow prophet of YHWH required a different kind of firmness.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The man of God's refusal of the old prophet uses identical language to his refusal of the king — suggesting he recognizes the structural equivalence of both invitations as threats to his mission independence. His explanation is transparent: he recounts the divine prohibition without attempting to deceive or soften it. This transparency will make the old prophet's lie more effective.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The man of God rehearses the divine command — all three elements (no bread, no water, no return by the same way). The repetition of the command through multiple retellings is a literary device that emphasizes its precision and total authority. Every element of the prohibition is clear; the subsequent failure will not be from misunderstanding.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The old prophet's lie — &ldquo;an angel spoke to me by the word of the LORD, saying, 'Bring him back with you to your house, that he may eat bread and drink water'&rdquo; — represents one of the most theologically significant episodes in the Deuteronomic History. It illustrates Deut 13:1&ndash;5: even a prophet who gives signs and wonders must be rejected if his message contradicts a prior command of YHWH. The appeal to angelic mediation makes the deception more plausible and harder to refute.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The man of God &ldquo;went back with him&rdquo; — a three-word sentence in the Hebrew that closes off the narrative of successful obedience. The failure is presented without psychological explanation: we are not told why he believed the lie, whether he was tired, lonely, or simply deceived. The narrative interest is not in his psychology but in the theological principle: a secondary revelation cannot override an explicit divine command, regardless of its prophetic source.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The word of YHWH comes to the old prophet — not to the man of God — at the table, during the meal. The irony is sharp: the man who delivered the false message now becomes the vehicle of the true one. This pattern (true prophecy delivered through an unlikely or compromised vessel) recurs in biblical narrative (cf. Balaam in Num 22&ndash;24; Caiaphas in John 11:51). The word of YHWH is not controlled by the virtue of its human instrument.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The oracle of judgment is addressed to &ldquo;the man of God who came from Judah&rdquo; — his identifying title, not his name. The indictment is precise: he disobeyed the mouth of YHWH and did not keep the command that YHWH commanded him. The narrative has been at pains to establish that the command was clear, specific, and thrice repeated (vv9, 16, 17) before this verdict falls.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;Your body shall not come to the grave of your fathers&rdquo; — denial of ancestral burial was one of the most severe judgments in ancient Israelite culture. Proper burial in the family tomb (<em>qeḇer ʾăḇōtāw</em>) united the dead with their kin in both a social and a symbolic sense. Burial far from home, without family mourning, in foreign soil, represented complete severance from community and covenant identity.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The old prophet's immediate action after the meal — saddling the donkey — shows that he accepts the oracle as genuine and prepares for the man of God's departure. The gesture of hospitality (saddling a guest's animal) takes on tragic irony: the old prophet is both the cause of the man of God's death sentence and the one who tenderly sends him on his final journey.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A lion kills the man of God on the road — but the lion does not eat the body and does not harm the donkey. In ancient Near Eastern tradition, lions were divine instruments and royal symbols. A lion that kills but does not eat, and that coexists peacefully with the donkey, signals divine rather than natural agency. The scene will be confirmed as extraordinary in v28. The death is understood as divine judgment, not random violence.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Passersby see the body, the donkey, and the lion standing together — an inexplicable sight that they report in Bethel. The lion's continued presence beside the body rather than fleeing (natural lion behavior after a kill) signals to all who hear that this is not an ordinary predator attack. The report spreads, drawing the old prophet out to the scene.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The old prophet's interpretation: &ldquo;He disobeyed the word of the LORD — therefore the LORD has given him to the lion.&rdquo; The old prophet now speaks prophetic interpretation, not deception. His acknowledgment that the man of God's death is divine judgment implicitly confesses his own role in the tragedy, though the text does not press the moral accounting. The community's understanding of the event is formed by this prophetic gloss.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The old prophet sends his sons for the body. His handling of the aftermath — retrieving the body, mourning, and burying it in his own tomb — transforms him from passive bystander to active participant in honoring the dead man. This trajectory of the old prophet from deceiver to mourner to custodian is one of the narrative's strangest and most human threads.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The sight at the road confirms supernatural restraint: the lion has not eaten the body and has not harmed the donkey. The donkey and the lion stand together beside the human corpse — predator, prey-animal, and human victim in an impossible tableau. This is the narrator's clearest signal that the scene enacts divine judgment rather than natural predation, establishing the pattern that Israelite audiences would read as divine <em>mišpāṭ</em> (judgment).</p>",
    "29": "<p>The body is laid on the donkey and brought back to the city of the old prophet. The &ldquo;city&rdquo; is Bethel — the very place the man of God was explicitly forbidden to enter or eat in (v9). The irony is layered: he enters Bethel in death, carried in honor by the prophet who deceived him into his doom.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The old prophet lays the body in his own tomb and leads the mourning: &ldquo;Alas, my brother!&rdquo; (<em>hôy ʾāḥî</em>) — a mourning cry used for deaths perceived as unjust or premature (Jer 22:18; Amos 5:16). The title &ldquo;my brother&rdquo; expresses prophetic solidarity even in the wake of betrayal. The mourning is genuine, the grief real — the old prophet understands what he caused.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The old prophet's instruction to his sons about his own future burial — &ldquo;bury me in the grave where the man of God is buried; lay my bones beside his bones&rdquo; — serves two purposes. It is an act of posthumous prophetic solidarity: to rest beside the man whose oracle proved true is to be associated with genuine prophecy. It also serves the oracle of v2: when Josiah desecrates the Bethel altar (2 Kgs 23:15&ndash;18), the old prophet's bones buried with the man of God will be spared on account of the true prophet's bones alongside them.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The old prophet affirms the oracle against the Bethel altar and against all the shrines of the cities of Samaria as certain of fulfillment. His confession comes too late to save the man of God but establishes the narrative's theological framework: even in Bethel, among those who benefit from Jeroboam's cultic innovations, the validity of the Judahite prophet's word is known and acknowledged.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;Even after this, Jeroboam did not turn from his evil ways.&rdquo; The miraculous sign (withered/restored hand), the split altar, and the prophetic oracle and its painful fulfillment produced no repentance in Jeroboam. The narrative of the man of God thus functions as a counterpoint to ch12: even dramatic divine intervention does not move a king whose religious policy is grounded in political calculation rather than covenantal loyalty.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;This became the sin of the house of Jeroboam&rdquo; (<em>wayᵉhî hadd̠āḇār hazzeh lᵉḥaṭṭāʾt bêt-yarāḇᵉʿām</em>) — the narrator's closing verdict on ch12&ndash;13. The &ldquo;sin of Jeroboam&rdquo; becomes a formulaic reference in the Deuteronomistic History (fourteen times in Kings), used to indict every northern king as following in Jeroboam's footsteps. The sin is both the golden calves and the non-Levitical priesthood — the twin innovations of 12:28&ndash;31.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The illness of Jeroboam's son Abijah serves as the narrative occasion for YHWH's definitive oracle against the dynasty. The juxtaposition of the child's illness with Jeroboam's cultic apostasy raises the implicit question of connection — ancient Near Eastern thought commonly linked royal sin with physical disaster to the royal household.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jeroboam's instruction for his wife to disguise herself reflects several cultural realities: Ahijah at Shiloh was the same prophet who had invested Jeroboam with the promise of kingship (11:29&ndash;39), but his subsequent behavior (the calves, non-Levitical priests) means Jeroboam cannot approach him openly. The disguise is a royal deception — Jeroboam fears that the prophet's word about the dynasty has changed and seeks the oracle clandestinely. Shiloh was the ancient home of the ark (1 Sam 1&ndash;4) and retained prestige as a prophetic site even after Jerusalem's rise.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The gift for the prophet — ten loaves of bread, cakes (<em>niqqud̠îm</em>, possibly hard crackers or dried figs), and a jar of honey — reflects the customary practice of bringing food to a seer or prophet when seeking a word (cf. 1 Sam 9:7&ndash;8). The items are provincial in character, appropriate to a woman in disguise as a commoner rather than a queen bearing royal gifts. The contrast between the modest gift and the royal commission exposes Jeroboam's anxiety.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahijah cannot see because his eyes were fixed (<em>qāmû ʿênāyw</em>) — a Hebrew idiom for the clouding of vision in old age (cf. Gen 27:1 for Isaac; 48:10 for Jacob). The prophet who once saw clearly enough to tear a garment and allocate ten pieces to Jeroboam (11:30) is now physically blind. The narrative inverts the expected: physical sight has failed, but prophetic sight — YHWH's forewarning in v5 — remains intact.</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH informs Ahijah of the approaching visitor, her identity, and the question she carries before she arrives. This pre-revelation pattern is standard in prophetic narrative: the true prophet does not rely on natural information-gathering but on YHWH's disclosure. The advance notice also sets up the unmasking scene in v6 as prophetically staged rather than coincidental.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ahijah's greeting — &ldquo;Come in, wife of Jeroboam&rdquo; — unmasks her before she speaks. The question &ldquo;Why do you pretend to be another woman?&rdquo; is rhetorical: Ahijah knows. The phrase &ldquo;I am sent to you with a harsh message&rdquo; (<em>ʾānōkî šālûaḥ ʾēlayik qāšāh</em>) uses the same root (<em>qāšāh</em>) as Rehoboam's harsh answer in 12:13 and the harsh labor of 12:4. The language of severity pervades this narrative unit.</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH's oracle begins with covenant preamble: &ldquo;I raised you up from among the people&rdquo; (<em>ʾărîmᵉkā mittôk hāʿām</em>) — language that echoes the election of Saul (1 Sam 9:16) and David (2 Sam 7:8). The gift of kingship is presented as pure divine initiative, not earned or inherited. This prologue establishes the covenantal context for the judgment that follows: Jeroboam received something extraordinary and failed to reciprocate with covenantal faithfulness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The comparison to David is programmatic in Kings. David is the standard against whom all subsequent kings are measured, and the quality specified here is that David &ldquo;followed me with all his heart, doing only what was right in my eyes.&rdquo; The kings of Israel and Judah are evaluated throughout the book by their approximation to or deviation from this standard. The Davidic covenant functions as the regulative ideal even in its critique of Jeroboam.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;You have done more evil than all who came before you&rdquo; — a superlative indictment. This formula will be applied to later kings (Ahab in 16:30, 33; Manasseh in 2 Kgs 21:9, 11), creating an escalating rhetoric of apostasy. Jeroboam's specific sin — casting other gods and metal images, &ldquo;provoking me to anger&rdquo; (<em>lᵉhakʿisênî</em>) — uses the language of marital jealousy that Deuteronomy employs for covenant infidelity (Deut 4:25; 9:18; 31:29).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The curse formula — &ldquo;I will cut off from Jeroboam every male, whether slave or free in Israel&rdquo; (<em>hammaštin baqqîr</em>, lit. &ldquo;one who urinates against a wall&rdquo; — a crude idiom for any male person) — is a stock phrase for total dynastic annihilation that recurs for Baasha (16:11), Ahab (21:21), and Jehu (2 Kgs 9:8). Its repetition creates a pattern of divine warning and eventual fulfillment that structures the narrative of northern kings.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The threat of dogs eating the dead in the city and birds eating those in the field is the antithesis of honorable burial — the worst possible end in Israelite culture, associated with exposure to scavengers and total loss of bodily integrity after death. This is the fate of the condemned in warfare (Deut 28:26) and becomes a standard element of covenant-curse oracles (Jer 7:33; 16:4). The formula underscores the totality of Jeroboam's dynastic extinction.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The moment your feet enter the city, the child will die&rdquo; — the threshold serves as the precise moment of death. Thresholds had significance in ancient Near Eastern culture as liminal spaces between outside and inside, between the public and domestic realms. The threshold-death creates a sign that confirms Ahijah's word: when the queen crosses from road to house, the oracle is fulfilled instantaneously.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Abijah will receive proper burial and national mourning — &ldquo;all Israel shall mourn for him&rdquo; — because &ldquo;in him alone of Jeroboam's house was found something pleasing to the LORD God of Israel.&rdquo; The child's early death is framed as mercy: he is spared the shameful end of the rest of the dynasty. This is one of the most theologically acute observations in Kings — the death that appears as loss is identified as grace, the judgment on the dynasty being avoidance of a worse fate.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The oracle anticipates a future king who will &ldquo;cut off the house of Jeroboam today, even now&rdquo; — the last phrase is ambiguous (<em>ûmeh gam-ʿāttāh</em>), possibly meaning &ldquo;yes, even now it begins.&rdquo; The fulfillment comes through Baasha, who kills Nadab son of Jeroboam and eliminates the entire dynasty (15:27&ndash;30). Ahijah's prophecy spans decades — Jeroboam dies of natural causes, but his house is cut off in the next generation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD will strike Israel as a reed is shaken in the water&rdquo; — the image of a reed swaying in a current captures both vulnerability and continuity: Israel will be shaken but not immediately cut off. The oracle then extends to exile: YHWH will &ldquo;uproot Israel from this good land which he gave to their fathers and scatter them beyond the Euphrates.&rdquo; This is the earliest explicit exile prophecy in Kings, connecting the northern kingdom's eventual deportation (722 BCE) directly to Jeroboam's founding sins.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;He will give Israel up&rdquo; (<em>yittēn et-yiśrāʾēl</em>) because of Jeroboam's sin — but also because Jeroboam &ldquo;caused Israel to sin.&rdquo; The theological point is precise: the king's sin is not merely personal apostasy but the corruption of the whole nation through the alternative cult centers. Corporate accountability flows from the king's institutional power to shape worship practice. The same logic will apply to Manasseh in 2 Kings.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jeroboam's wife returns to Tirzah — a city that became the northern capital after Shechem. Tirzah is mentioned in the Song of Solomon as a byword for beauty (Song 6:4), and it served as the capital until Omri built Samaria (16:23&ndash;24). The threshold death fulfills the oracle precisely: the child dies as the queen crosses from the road into the house.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The burial and national mourning fulfills the oracle of v13. The narrator confirms completeness: &ldquo;as the LORD had said through his servant Ahijah the prophet.&rdquo; The explicit fulfillment notice is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic framework throughout Kings: prophecy is given, time passes, and the fulfillment is marked — establishing YHWH's sovereign control over history through the prophetic word.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;The Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel&rdquo; is the first reference to what appears to have been an official annalistic record of the northern monarchy — distinct from the canonical books of Chronicles. It is cited throughout Kings as a source for military and administrative details beyond the theological-didactic focus of the Kings narrative. The formula &ldquo;are they not written in&rdquo; invites readers to consult these records while signaling that Kings selects for a different purpose.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jeroboam reigns twenty-two years — the longest reign of any king in the north until Menahem. He &ldquo;rested with his ancestors&rdquo; — the standard formula for a peaceful death, even for a condemned king. The dynasty is not immediately cut off; Nadab his son succeeds him. The tension between Ahijah's oracle of dynastic termination and Jeroboam's natural death creates the expectation of second-generation judgment that will be fulfilled in 15:27&ndash;30.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The narrative shifts to the southern kingdom — Rehoboam son of Solomon. He is forty-one at accession, suggesting he was born during Solomon's early reign, likely to Naamah the Ammonite (v31), a diplomatic wife. The seventeen-year reign (931&ndash;914 BCE) is confirmed by synchronization with the northern kings. Jerusalem is described as the city &ldquo;which the LORD had chosen out of all the tribes of Israel to put his name there&rdquo; — the Deuteronomic formula for the chosen sanctuary that recurs throughout Kings.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Judah &ldquo;provoked him to jealousy&rdquo; (<em>wayᵉqannᵉʾû</em>) more than their ancestors — the language of marital jealousy, drawn from the Deuteronomic understanding of covenant as analogous to marriage (Deut 32:16, 21; Ezek 16). This jealousy-language is reserved for the most serious apostasy: not mere ritual error but the fundamental violation of exclusive loyalty to YHWH.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The three elements of Canaanite cult — high places (<em>bāmôt</em>), sacred pillars (<em>maṣṣēḇôt</em>), and Asherah poles (<em>ʾăšērîm</em>) — represent the full apparatus of indigenous Palestinian worship that Israel was commanded to destroy (Deut 12:2&ndash;3). Sacred pillars (<em>maṣṣēḇôt</em>) were upright stone steles representing divine presence or commemorating covenant; Asherah poles were wooden cult objects associated with the goddess Asherah (attested in the Kuntillet Ajrud inscriptions, 8th century). &ldquo;Under every green tree&rdquo; is a formulaic phrase for outdoor nature worship.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The <em>qᵉdēšîm</em> (sing. <em>qādēš</em>, lit. &ldquo;holy one&rdquo; or &ldquo;consecrated person&rdquo;) remain debated. The traditional translation &ldquo;male cult prostitutes&rdquo; connects them to Mesopotamian and Syrian temple personnel involved in sacred sexuality; modern scholars often prefer &ldquo;male cult functionaries&rdquo; given the ambiguity of the evidence for cultic prostitution in ancient Israel. The Deuteronomic law explicitly forbids both male and female <em>qādēš</em> (Deut 23:18). The narrator's charge that Judah &ldquo;practiced all the abominations of the nations&rdquo; invokes the Canaanite-contamination framework of Deut 18:9&ndash;14.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Shishak king of Egypt (Shoshenq I of the Twenty-Second Dynasty) invaded in Rehoboam's fifth year — approximately 925 BCE. This is one of the most archaeologically confirmed events in the narrative: Shoshenq's own victory inscription at the Temple of Karnak at Luxor lists over 150 conquered Canaanite and Israelite cities, including towns in both Judah and Israel, confirming the geographic scope of the campaign. The invasion came shortly after the division of the kingdom, when both successor states were politically vulnerable.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Shishak carries off the treasures of the temple and the palace — including the golden shields Solomon had made (10:16&ndash;17). The shields, like the temple furniture, represented the accumulated wealth of Solomon's era. Their removal marks the transition from the Solomonic golden age to the reduced circumstances of Rehoboam's reign. The detailed catalog (&ldquo;everything&rdquo;) emphasizes the totality of the loss.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The replacement of gold shields with bronze ones captures the trajectory of decline in miniature. Bronze is the alloy of the previous age — capable, functional, but no longer the prestige material of the Solomonic court. The substitution of bronze for gold is a material metaphor for the diminishment of both the monarchy and its relationship with YHWH.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The guards bring the shields for each royal procession to the temple and then return them to the guardroom — a ceremonial ritual that maintains the appearance of Solomonic splendor while acknowledging the change in material. The continued use of the shields as ceremonial objects rather than simply discarding them shows the court's need to sustain the legitimating symbols of the Davidic monarchy even in diminished circumstances.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The reference to &ldquo;the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah&rdquo; parallels the source citation for Jeroboam in v19. Kings maintains parallel administrative frameworks for north and south — each monarchy has its annalistic record. The symmetry of citation reinforces the Deuteronomistic schema: both kingdoms are subject to the same evaluative standard and the same historiographic documentation.</p>",
    "30": "<p>War between Rehoboam and Jeroboam &ldquo;throughout their reigns&rdquo; — a continuous state of border conflict rather than a single decisive war. The geographic fault line between the two kingdoms ran through the tribal territory of Benjamin, and control of border cities and trade routes meant constant low-level military competition. No major battle is recorded in Kings for this period; the conflict is described as endemic rather than episodic.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Rehoboam is buried &ldquo;in the city of David&rdquo; — in the royal tombs of Jerusalem, maintaining the dynastic continuity of the Davidic line in its ancestral city. His mother Naamah the Ammonite is mentioned at accession (v21) and again at death, framing his reign with her identity. As the mother of the king (<em>gᵉḇîrāh</em>, queen mother), she was a significant political figure; her Ammonite origin may have contributed to the syncretistic religious policies of the reign. Abijam his son succeeds him.</p>"
  }
}

